# GitHub Workflow Rules

## Commit Messages

### Format
Use conventional commit format: `type(scope): description`

### Types
- `feat`: New feature
- `fix`: Bug fix
- `docs`: Documentation only
- `style`: Formatting, no code change
- `refactor`: Code change that neither fixes nor adds
- `test`: Adding or updating tests
- `chore`: Build process, dependencies, etc.

### Guidelines
- Keep subject line under 50 characters
- Use imperative mood ("Add feature" not "Added feature")
- Don't end subject line with period
- Add body for complex changes (separated by blank line)

### Examples
```
feat(contracts): add file upload component
fix(auth): resolve session refresh issue
docs(readme): update setup instructions
refactor(api): simplify Supabase query functions
style(ui): fix inconsistent button padding
test(contracts): add unit tests for validation
chore(deps): update TanStack Query to v5
```

### Phase-Based Commits (Surgical Coding Workflow)
When working through implementation phases:
```
feat(contract-review): complete 01-db-updates
feat(contract-review): complete 02-api-updates
feat(contract-review): complete 03-ui-updates
```

## Before Committing

### Checklist
- [ ] Code compiles without errors (`npm run build`)
- [ ] No console.log statements in production code
- [ ] No secrets or API keys in code
- [ ] Feature works as expected
- [ ] TypeScript types are correct (no `any`)
- [ ] Linter passes (if configured)

### Security Check
- Never commit .env files
- Never commit API keys or secrets
- Use .gitignore for sensitive files
- Check `git diff` before committing

## Branching Strategy

### Branch Naming
- `feature/description` - new features
- `fix/description` - bug fixes
- `refactor/description` - code improvements

### Workflow
1. Create branch from main: `git checkout -b feature/my-feature`
2. Make changes and commit frequently
3. Push to remote: `git push -u origin feature/my-feature`
4. Create pull request when ready
5. Merge after review (auto-deploys to Vercel)

## Replit ↔ Cursor Workflow

### Replit → GitHub → Cursor
```bash
# In Replit
git add .
git commit -m "feat(feature-name): description"
git push

# In Cursor terminal
git pull origin main
```

### Cursor → GitHub → Replit
```bash
# In Cursor terminal
git add .
git commit -m "feat(feature-name): description"
git push

# In Replit
git pull origin main
```

## When Asked to Commit

Follow this process:
1. Stage relevant files: `git add [files]`
2. Review changes: `git diff --staged`
3. Commit with descriptive message using format above
4. Push to remote branch

Do not push to main directly unless instructed.
